  "sections": [
    { "tag": "section", "className": "hero",   "bgMode": "bulletin", "bgColor": "#e8d8b8", "colorMode": "#1a1410", "childTextSnippet": "THE HOLLER. I grew up here. I still do. [Wendell portrait — pearl-snap shirt, no smile, real.]" },
    { "tag": "section", "className": "origin", "bgMode": "bulletin", "bgColor": "#e8d8b8", "colorMode": "#1a1410", "childTextSnippet": "I grew up in a hollow outside Asheville where my grandmother kept a still in the smokehouse and a hymnal on the kitchen table. We never thought of them as different things. The botanicals come from the same woods that grew the rhododendron my grandfather got married under. The recipes come from the same Sunday afternoons that grew the hymns. Everything in these bottles is foraged or grown within forty miles of my barn. Nothing is bought in a jug. The labels are painted by hand, by me, in a shed I bought off a dead preacher. — Wendell" },
    { "tag": "section", "className": "place",  "bgMode": "revival", "bgColor": "#1a1410", "colorMode": "#e8d8b8", "childTextSnippet": "Wolfpen Holler — Madison County, NC. Forty minutes outside Asheville. Mars Hill on the south edge. Pisgah on the east. The Tennessee line on the north. Rhododendron understory. Sourwood blossom in late June. [Landscape image.]" },
    { "tag": "section", "className": "anchor", "bgMode": "bulletin", "bgColor": "#e8d8b8", "colorMode": "#1a1410", "childTextSnippet": "We never thought of them as different things. The smokehouse was where the still lived. The kitchen was where the hymnal lived. Both got used every week." },
    { "tag": "section", "className": "why",    "bgMode": "revival", "bgColor": "#1a1410", "colorMode": "#e8d8b8", "childTextSnippet": "Started in 2019 because nobody else was making this. The kit came from a man in Tennessee. He drew me a diagram on the back of a feed-store receipt. I still have the receipt." }
  ],
